05608nam a22008295i 9780812296136DE-B159720210621102733.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||210621t20192019pau    fo  d z      eng d  a97808122961367 a10.9783/97808122961362doi  a(DE-B1597)530593  a(OCoLC)1101792219  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  apaucUS-PA 4aBS2575.53b.S6513 2019 7aREL0061002bisacsh04a226/.2061 aSoloveitchik, Elijah Zvi, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut14aThe Bible, the Talmud, and the New Testament :bElijah Zvi Soloveitchik's Commentary to the Gospels /cElijah Zvi Soloveitchik; ed. by Shaul Magid. 1aPhiladelphia : bUniversity of Pennsylvania Press, c[2019] 4c©2019  a1 online resource (440 p.) :b1 illus.  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aJewish Culture and Contexts00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tForeword -- tIntroduction: Elĳah Zvi Soloveitchik, the Jewish Jesus, Christianity, and the Jews -- tA Note on the Text -- tA Translator’s Foreword -- tTHE COMMENTARIES -- tDedication -- tA Word to the Reader -- tAuthor’s Preface -- tThe Gospel According to Matthew, with Commentary -- tThe Gospel According to Mark, with Commentary -- tBibliography -- tIndex of Names -- tIndex of Texts -- tAcknowledgments0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aBorn in Slutzk, Russia, in 1805, Elijah Zvi Soloveitchik is a largely forgotten member of the prestigious Soloveitchik rabbinic dynasty. Before Hayyim Soloveitchik developed the standard Brisker method of Talmudic study, or Joseph Dov Soloveitchik helped to found American Modern Orthodox Judaism, Elijah Soloveitchik wrote Qol Qore, a rabbinic commentary on the Gospels of Matthew and Mark. Qol Qore drew on classic rabbinic literature, and particularly on the works of Moses Maimonides, to argue for the compatibility of Christianity with Judaism. To this day, it remains the only rabbinic work to embrace the compatability of Orthodox Judaism and the Christian Bible.In The Bible, the Talmud, and the New Testament, Shaul Magid presents the first-ever English translation of Qol Qore. In his contextualizing introduction, Magid explains that Qol Qore offers a window onto the turbulent historical context of nineteenth-century European Jewry. With violent anti-Semitic activity on the rise in Europe, Elijah Soloveitchik was unique in believing that the roots of anti-Semitism were theological, based on a misunderstanding of the New Testament by both Jews and Christians. His hope was that the Qol Qore, written in Hebrew and translated into French, German, and Polish, would reach Jewish and Christian audiences alike, urging each to consider the validity of the other's religious principles. In an era characterized by fractious debates between Jewish communities, Elijah Soloveitchik represents a voice that called for radical unity amongst Jews and Christians alike.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 21. Jun 2021) 0aChristianity and other religionsxJudaism. 0aJudaismxRelationsxChristianity. 0aRabbinical literaturexRelation to the New Testament. 7aRELIGION / Biblical Criticism & Interpretation / New Testament.2bisacsh  aJewish Studies.  aReligion.  aReligious Studies.1 aLevy, Jordan Gayle.1 aMagid, Shaul, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aSalovey, Peter.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE COMPLETE 2019 Englishz978311061076508iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE COMPLETE 2019z9783110664232oZDB-23-DGG08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE Theol., Relig. Stud., Jewish Stud.2019 Englishz978311061074108iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE Theology, Relig. Studies, Jewish Studies 2019z9